  "market_context": "ETH was trading in a consolidation range after a move lower with a slow V-shaped recovery. Price closed back above the range and reached into a fair value gap, simultaneously taking out a short-term high — a potential scenario two setup.",
  "key_observation": "After running the short-term/range high, price failed to form a continuation candle and instead came back aggressively across the range, showing the breakout was manipulation rather than a genuine expansion.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified prior consolidation range with a move lower followed by a slow V-shaped recovery.",
    "Step 2: Noted price closing back over the range and reaching into a fair value gap while simultaneously taking out a short-term high (scenario two).",
    "Step 3: Considered two options — trust the setup and enter expecting the low to hold, or wait to see if continuation forms.",
    "Step 4: Chose to wait for the next candle to confirm whether continuation or reversal would occur.",
    "Step 5: Observed price came back across the range aggressively, invalidating the breakout and confirming it was manipulation.",
    "Step 6: Concluded that waiting saved a losing trade, and any long entry would require a new V-shaped recovery for confirmation."
  ],
  "outcome": "Waiting for confirmation saved the trader from a loss — no entry taken since continuation never formed.",
  "lessons": "When price runs short-term highs out of a range, do not assume the breakout is real. Wait for a continuation candle to confirm directional intent; otherwise the run may be manipulation back across the range.",
